# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the MKapu Import e-commerce Next.js application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- **Added dependency**: `@vercel/speed-insights` version ^2.0.0
- **Package manager**: npm
- **Files modified**: 
  - `package.json` - Added @vercel/speed-insights to dependencies
  - `package-lock.json` - Updated with new dependency tree

### 2. SpeedInsights Component Integration
- **File modified**: `src/app/layout.tsx`
- **Changes**:
  - Imported `SpeedInsights` component from `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
  - Added `<SpeedInsights />` component to the root layout inside the `<body>` tag
  - Component placed after the main CartProvider wrapper to ensure it tracks all page interactions

### 3. Implementation Details
Following the official Vercel documentation (fetched from https://vercel.com/docs/speed-insights/quickstart):
- Used the Next.js-specific import path: `@vercel/speed-insights/next`
- Placed the component at the root layout level to track performance across all pages
- Positioned component within the `<body>` tag as recommended for optimal data collection

## Framework Context
- **Framework**: Next.js 16.2.3 (App Router)
- **TypeScript**: Yes
- **Root Layout**: Uses App Router with `src/app/layout.tsx`

## Verification
✅ Build completed successfully - no errors introduced
✅ Package installed without vulnerabilities
✅ TypeScript compilation passed
✅ No new linting errors introduced (existing errors are pre-existing)
✅ Lock files updated correctly

## Next Steps
After deploying to Vercel:
1. Enable Speed Insights in the Vercel dashboard
2. Navigate to your project settings
3. Select "Speed Insights" from the sidebar
4. Click "Enable" to start collecting performance metrics

Once enabled, Speed Insights will automatically begin tracking Core Web Vitals and performance metrics for real user sessions.
